iMy ASUS laptop originally had a sound card driver in Windows 7 that		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iincluded a technology called ASUS Sonic Focus. Its principle involves		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iadjusting the audio equalizer to create a psychological Dolby surround		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieffect, making listeners perceive the sound as spatial. After enabling		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSonic Focus, I found the audio quality significantly improved. (I'm		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inot an audiophile.)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, on Ubuntu, there's naturally no Sonic Focus – ASUS wouldn't		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibother supporting such a rapidly evolving system. Dolby and SRS also		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idon't provide Linux support, so the open-source community developed		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iExtra Stereo to replicate these features. There's also Crystalizer,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich enhances high-frequency loudness for clearer sound. Those who've		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iused Creative Sound Blaster or X-Fi cards should be familiar with		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithis.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
