iMeanwhile, the most frustrating aspect of listening to music on Ubuntu		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iis the lack of lyrics. Rhythmbox claims to have automatic lyric		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idownloading, but it simply didn't work for me... I had to search for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ialternatives myself.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThat's when I discovered OSD Lyrics.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i> OSD Lyrics is a lyrics show compatible with various media players.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIt is not a plugin but a standalone program. OSD Lyrics shows lyrics		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion your desktop, in the style similar to KaraOK. It also provides		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ianother displaying style, in which lyrics scroll from bottom to top.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iOSD Lyrics can download lyrics from the network automatically.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis software displays desktop lyrics and supports Audacious, Banshee		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(pre-installed in Ubuntu 12.04 or 11.10, I forget which), Rhythmbox		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(pre-installed in Ubuntu 12.10), and others. Its effects resemble Kuwo		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ior similar players, and it can automatically search/download lyrics		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom the Qianqian Jinting lyrics database. The official PPA repository		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iallows direct installation:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBy default, lyrics are stored in `~/.lyrics`, which is inconvenient. I		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprefer storing them with the music files. Open OSD Lyrics (it will		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iprompt you to select a player), click the icon in the top-right corner		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i→ Options → Lyrics Location. Clear the path field except for `%`, and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithe filename field except for `%f`.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Enabling SRS WOW-like Sound Effects		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis is trickier since Extra Stereo isn't a standalone install or		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idriver-level feature. We need a compatible player. Currently supported		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplayers include MPlayer (SMPlayer) and Audacious. For music, we'll use		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAudacious.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter installation, open Audacious. Go to the top menu: Output →		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iEffects, where you'll find both Crystalizer and Extra Stereo.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iPS:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor standard computer speakers:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Extra Stereo: Set around 2.8 (values >3.5 cause distortion)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Crystalizer: Set around 2 (values >3 cause distortion)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Echo: Configure as 180, 28, 24 (top to bottom)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor SMPlayer, you can either adjust settings per video or add them to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iMPlayer's launch parameters. Go to Menu → Options → Preferences →		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAdvanced. In the "Execute the following actions each time a file is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iopened" field, add:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSave the settings. Alternatively, enable manually via Menu → Audio →		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFilters → Extra Stereo.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}